00:14:21.576 --> 00:14:24.238
“He’d do anything for us
to have a good life.”

00:14:24.278 --> 00:14:25.820
“Yes, he was an alcoholic.”

00:14:26.856 --> 00:14:30.111
“If you were my father,
you’d probably be an alcoholic ”

00:14:30.189 --> 00:14:31.731
“just to escape poverty."

00:14:31.810 --> 00:14:34.999
“Even so, my father never left me."

00:14:35.273 --> 00:14:41.787
“If only he didn’t burn
with the basement of fertilizers,”

00:14:41.812 --> 00:14:43.130
“he’d still be alive.”

00:14:43.189 --> 00:14:45.755
“No. What happened
wasn’t an accident.”

00:14:45.814 --> 00:14:47.236
“Someone killed him.”

00:14:47.295 --> 00:14:49.639
“I saw it with my own eyes
while the basement was on fire.”

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:51.866
“It was locked from the outside.”

00:14:51.964 --> 00:14:54.964
“Do you think cats
could lock a basement?”

00:14:55.038 --> 00:14:56.288
“You’re right. It can’t”

00:14:56.659 --> 00:15:00.956
“I’m sure of it.
My father was murdered.”

00:15:01.037 --> 00:15:04.084
“Now, tell me I’m not a failure."

00:15:04.407 --> 00:15:05.407
“Who?”

00:15:05.724 --> 00:15:06.617
“That was a long time ago.”

00:15:06.676 --> 00:15:09.197
“And she’s happy
with the life she chose.”

00:15:09.237 --> 00:15:12.148
“She should be happy!
If not, then that’s karma.”

00:15:12.198 --> 00:15:14.648
“I believe in karma.”

00:15:14.708 --> 00:15:18.722
“Whatever you do to others,
will come back to you.”

00:15:18.805 --> 00:15:20.399
“Sometimes, much more to you.”

00:15:20.771 --> 00:15:23.075
“What do I care
if her husband hits her?”

00:15:23.149 --> 00:15:26.120
“That’s just right so she can
at least feel the pain I felt”

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:28.910
“when she left me for another man.”

00:15:29.535 --> 00:15:31.058
“She’s just like my mother.”

00:15:31.386 --> 00:15:33.617
“Never content with what she has.”

00:15:33.642 --> 00:15:36.747
“Not caring even if she hurts people.”

00:15:36.831 --> 00:15:39.897
“Go ahead! She’s not the one in pain.”

00:15:40.425 --> 00:15:41.592
“Karma is real.”

00:15:41.670 --> 00:15:43.341
“And it’ll come at her doorstep.”

00:15:43.531 --> 00:15:46.606
“Like an incurable disease.”

00:15:46.854 --> 00:15:49.509
“And if it doesn’t come to her?”

00:15:49.683 --> 00:15:50.776
“I tell you.”

00:15:51.008 --> 00:15:57.435
“I’ll be karma itself
until she regrets the day she left me.”

00:15:57.497 --> 00:16:01.552
“I’m a failure, but they’ll see
I won’t be alone.”

00:16:01.725 --> 00:16:08.817
“Like what they did to me,
I’ll crush them into the failures they are.

00:16:09.073 --> 00:16:11.940
Right now, he doesn’t sound like a priest.

00:16:13.582 --> 00:16:17.095
He seems like a priest in label only.

00:16:19.075 --> 00:16:22.291
- Sorry, why did he become a priest?

00:16:22.416 --> 00:16:26.844
- He became a priest to escape
what was done to him.

00:16:26.906 --> 00:16:28.182
- By the two girls?

00:16:28.457 --> 00:16:29.385
- The one girl.

00:16:29.424 --> 00:16:30.549
[inaudible]

00:16:30.612 --> 00:16:32.512
The one who married the mayor.

00:16:33.479 --> 00:16:39.064
- His anger when his girlfriend left him

00:16:39.143 --> 00:16:42.990
is a step back
to when his mother left him.

00:16:43.069 --> 00:16:49.397
- First, his mother left him.
Next, the woman he loved left him.

00:16:51.159 --> 00:16:53.513
- When I wrote this,

00:16:53.669 --> 00:16:57.591
it was a misbelief over something.

00:16:57.763 --> 00:16:59.976
- Of some facts
that he didn’t know about.

00:17:01.601 --> 00:17:04.635
- You asked a while ago,
how come he’s very angry here?

00:17:04.767 --> 00:17:06.127
- What does he know?

00:17:06.572 --> 00:17:09.062
- Just because she got married
he’s already so angry?

00:17:09.503 --> 00:17:16.127
Victor’s objective
is apparently revenge.

00:17:16.606 --> 00:17:19.321
When was that objective formed?

00:17:19.399 --> 00:17:23.578
When he became a priest
or when he was already in town?

00:17:23.759 --> 00:17:25.492
- When he got back to town.

00:17:25.577 --> 00:17:34.209
- The dialogue I thought of for this
was he didn’t see any change in the town.

00:17:34.312 --> 00:17:36.800
- When he left, it was still like that.

00:17:36.857 --> 00:17:40.070
- Even after ten years,
he’s still seeing the same things.

00:17:41.167 --> 00:17:42.456
Even the corruption.

00:17:42.989 --> 00:17:48.511
Even after priesthood?
How many years was that?

00:17:49.149 --> 00:17:51.563
About seven, I would say.

00:17:51.902 --> 00:17:57.901
- He was fourth year in philosophy
when his ex got married.

00:17:58.229 --> 00:18:02.166
- He studied priesthood for four years.

00:18:02.223 --> 00:18:07.494
Four. Three years outside.
How about other parishes?

00:18:07.901 --> 00:18:11.181
- Seven?
- It took 10 years for him to go back home.

00:18:11.728 --> 00:18:14.967
Ten years. So how old was he then?

00:18:15.030 --> 00:18:15.694
- Thirty.

00:18:15.739 --> 00:18:17.291
Thirty. And the girl?

00:18:17.425 --> 00:18:18.792
- About the same.

00:18:22.441 --> 00:18:29.760
In those ten years, with how he talks,
I imagine he’s so angry,

00:18:29.852 --> 00:18:32.008
In those ten years,

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:37.179
it's as if nothing affected
the way he talks.

00:18:37.314 --> 00:18:44.911
Because of his words and his anger,
of his all-consuming hate,

00:18:45.817 --> 00:18:52.796
I kind of hear the Victor
who hasn’t undergone priesthood yet.

00:18:53.177 --> 00:19:02.765
I didn’t see the angry Victor
who became a priest.

00:19:04.074 --> 00:19:16.034
That means he didn’t imbibe
the patience, virtues, philosophy he studied.

00:19:17.839 --> 00:19:20.940
I imagined him like a friar.

00:19:21.695 --> 00:19:24.807
He’s not the kind of priest
that we’re familiar with.

00:19:24.893 --> 00:19:29.377
He’s like Padre Damaso
who’s holding something in,

00:19:29.409 --> 00:19:32.210
but pleasant to everyone else.

00:19:32.264 --> 00:19:36.404
But even then,
the likes of Padre Damaso,

00:19:36.791 --> 00:19:47.267
the profanity that he spouts
is mixed with the religiosity he preaches.

00:19:48.321 --> 00:19:53.357
In fact, “In Jesus’ Name” is his litany.

00:19:53.437 --> 00:20:01.752
But here, there’s nothing like that,
which is what confuses me.

00:20:03.789 --> 00:20:09.913
- I still don’t know
how I’m going to weave it

00:20:09.972 --> 00:20:12.468
taking into consideration
what Rody said

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:15.028
that this is already
the devil talking

00:20:15.087 --> 00:20:18.230
even Padre Damaso
would have some goodness inside.

00:20:18.625 --> 00:20:22.628
No, it’s not the goodness
that I’m questioning.

00:20:25.142 --> 00:20:28.072
It’s the language that he uses.

00:20:32.354 --> 00:20:37.167
Even Maui is different.

00:20:38.321 --> 00:20:40.273
Why would a church

00:20:40.366 --> 00:20:53.832
in a farflung place allow
a flamboyant gay to live with them?

00:20:54.024 --> 00:20:59.311
They would, of course,
ask for propriety.

00:20:59.356 --> 00:21:02.658
If you want to do this,
do it but in a soft voice.

00:21:02.686 --> 00:21:05.218
Those kinds of strictures.

00:21:06.362 --> 00:21:08.557
In Victor’s monologue,

00:21:08.615 --> 00:21:12.646
I don’t feel the establishment
of the church

00:21:12.709 --> 00:21:15.616
because he’s not using
the language of the church.

00:21:15.874 --> 00:21:19.153
What he’s using
is the language of a peasant

00:21:20.017 --> 00:21:21.988
who is consumed with hate

00:21:24.754 --> 00:21:30.772
but Victor has already undergone
a training of priesthood

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:33.894
and part of that training is…

00:21:35.066 --> 00:21:41.019
for example, if you have an M.A.
and you’re angry,

00:21:41.917 --> 00:21:44.459
you talk differently.

00:21:45.426 --> 00:21:49.640
You use and rationalize
what you have learned

00:21:49.719 --> 00:21:56.128
so that you can deepen
the premise of your anger.

00:21:57.854 --> 00:22:03.244
I'm not saying turn Victor
into a soft-hearted person.

00:22:03.489 --> 00:22:04.890
It could be there

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:12.127
but he’s using
what he has learned in priesthood,

00:22:12.225 --> 00:22:16.025
what he has learned
in the establishment of the church

00:22:17.236 --> 00:22:19.853
so that he can also rationalize it.

00:22:20.887 --> 00:22:24.195
Like what you’re saying,
this is not revenge.

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:26.554
This is justice.

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:36.448
See, even that is already a perversion
of the tenets of the Catholic Church.

00:22:37.456 --> 00:22:39.323
That’s what I’m looking for.

00:22:39.360 --> 00:22:44.886
So that I can understand it better
and to convince myself

00:22:45.026 --> 00:22:48.384
that yes, he’s angry,
but he’s still a priest.

00:22:48.736 --> 00:22:51.956
In the same way
that we understand Padre Salvi.

00:22:53.044 --> 00:23:01.787
He’s quiet but the way he engineered
the death of Maria Clara and Crisostomo Ibarra

00:23:02.114 --> 00:23:06.235
using precisely the words of God.

00:23:07.357 --> 00:23:10.286
That looks more evil.

00:23:13.332 --> 00:23:21.595
Maybe that’s what would create
and shape your character uniquely.

00:23:23.625 --> 00:23:26.856
Because we’re talking
about a man of God

00:23:27.442 --> 00:23:30.413
and what we know of priests

00:23:30.491 --> 00:23:35.404
is that they’re always quiet and calm,

00:23:35.544 --> 00:23:36.999
But this is the opposite.

00:23:38.638 --> 00:23:41.872
But if you do it in reverse,
it may disappear.

00:23:41.951 --> 00:23:44.588
He still has to be

00:23:45.844 --> 00:23:47.281
a man of God.

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:50.252
But he distorted it.

00:23:52.198 --> 00:23:54.298
But we’re like that, right?

00:23:54.370 --> 00:23:57.370
Even if we’re corrupt,
we rationalize it

00:23:58.092 --> 00:23:59.995
because my child is like this,

00:24:00.038 --> 00:24:03.062
rather than him dying,
I’ll just accept what the mayor gave.

00:24:03.114 --> 00:24:04.708
Something like that, right?

00:24:04.779 --> 00:24:08.184
But that’s in the milieu that you have.

00:24:09.508 --> 00:24:11.452
In the same way, if that’s a priest,

00:24:11.526 --> 00:24:16.221
I’m sure they’re rationalizing it
in religious terms.

00:24:16.251 --> 00:24:19.064
- "I’m doing this because..."
- "Because of this."

00:24:19.147 --> 00:24:21.087
"As Jesus said,"

00:24:21.111 --> 00:24:22.938
You even quoted the Bible.

00:24:24.056 --> 00:24:27.670
"When the four horsemen
of the apocalypse arrive."

00:24:28.398 --> 00:24:29.170
I don’t know.

00:24:29.915 --> 00:24:34.397
Justice is waiting and so on.

00:24:35.643 --> 00:24:39.956
Maybe that’s where
the religious aspect comes in

00:24:40.761 --> 00:24:43.652
because the traces
of the establishment would disappear.

00:24:44.125 --> 00:24:47.336
- Do you have more suggestions?

00:24:47.471 --> 00:24:51.975
- In terms of the character’s objective
that should be important to the protagonist?

00:24:52.047 --> 00:24:57.194
Usually the character’s objective
is conceptual in the mind of the writer.

00:24:57.255 --> 00:25:00.542
For example, she’s looking
for happiness or something

00:25:00.676 --> 00:25:06.723
or sometimes it works
if the objective is physical

00:25:06.816 --> 00:25:10.910
like she needs to pass the bar exams
or to go to Batanes.

00:25:11.846 --> 00:25:13.374
How do you balance it?

00:25:13.484 --> 00:25:18.230
Or do you have suggestions
on how to articulate the objectives

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:23.423
whether it’s for conceptual
or physical?

00:25:23.530 --> 00:25:26.173
It has to be very concrete and specific.

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:28.227
It cannot be “I want love.”

00:25:28.531 --> 00:25:30.235
"I want to feel love. "

00:25:30.552 --> 00:25:32.574
That doesn’t mean anything.

00:25:33.374 --> 00:25:35.359
It has to be very specific.

00:25:35.668 --> 00:25:36.668
"I want.."

00:25:38.936 --> 00:25:41.454
"my mother to come here and embrace me "

00:25:42.542 --> 00:25:47.119
"...because she has been away
for so long and she has ignored me. "

00:25:47.938 --> 00:25:49.845
It can be that specific.

00:25:51.762 --> 00:25:55.556
But it still has to be an all-consuming desire.

00:25:55.836 --> 00:25:57.385
Desire for revenge,

00:25:57.764 --> 00:26:01.369
desire for closure.

00:26:02.492 --> 00:26:07.534
The writer needs to be conscious
so it need not be articulated.

00:26:07.781 --> 00:26:10.054
That is the reason why you’re dramatizing it.

00:26:10.671 --> 00:26:14.784
You don’t need to say
at a certain point that he’s going to say that.

00:26:14.819 --> 00:26:15.627
No.

00:26:16.398 --> 00:26:20.961
He could hide or, in fact, deny it

00:26:23.374 --> 00:26:25.059
because he was rationalizing.

00:26:25.101 --> 00:26:26.817
For example, even revenge,

00:26:27.299 --> 00:26:29.610
he could also deny it,
“I’m not out for revenge."

00:26:31.119 --> 00:26:32.594
"I’m just out for justice”

00:26:32.664 --> 00:26:34.750
Which in fact can be the same thing.

00:26:38.043 --> 00:26:41.337
So there are many ways to execute it.

00:26:41.904 --> 00:26:43.214
And the best way

00:26:43.259 --> 00:26:46.682
is when you say something

00:26:46.745 --> 00:26:48.651
without explicitly saying it.

00:26:49.125 --> 00:26:51.296
The audience is the one who says it.

00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:53.280
“Ah, he wants love.”

00:26:54.015 --> 00:26:58.161
When she says that,
without you saying it at all in your play,

00:26:58.266 --> 00:26:59.772
even the very word,

00:27:02.144 --> 00:27:03.508
then you achieved it.

00:27:04.884 --> 00:27:07.682
But to be more concrete in terms of objective,

00:27:08.093 --> 00:27:09.709
that’s the most important.

00:27:10.578 --> 00:27:14.858
Tomorrow, we’ll find out
how to make this more vivid.

00:27:15.236 --> 00:27:19.064
Because you can’t really show
what the character wants

00:27:19.179 --> 00:27:20.603
if there is no

00:27:21.446 --> 00:27:22.798
obstacle.

00:27:23.084 --> 00:27:25.354
Because if you don’t put an obstacle,

00:27:26.475 --> 00:27:27.815
then she easily achieves it.

00:27:30.689 --> 00:27:32.657
She easily achieves it.

00:27:32.764 --> 00:27:37.396
Now, if you put an obstacle,
what he wants becomes clearer.

00:27:37.715 --> 00:27:40.073
And the question, “Is he going to get it or not?”

00:27:40.098 --> 00:27:42.793
becomes clearer to the audience

00:27:43.815 --> 00:27:46.017
which is why it’s integral—

00:27:46.231 --> 00:27:49.796
the relationship of the character and the conflict.

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:52.951
Right now, some of your characters

00:27:53.012 --> 00:27:56.206
have not articulated what they really want.

00:27:57.195 --> 00:27:59.273
And that’s why I’m asking you, writers,

00:27:59.538 --> 00:28:01.185
whether you know or not.

00:28:01.272 --> 00:28:04.231
Because if the character doesn’t know,
it’s probably alright.

00:28:04.265 --> 00:28:06.538
But if the writer doesn’t know,
then you have a problem.

00:28:06.588 --> 00:28:10.423
I’m not saying you
should have an answer right now.

00:28:10.478 --> 00:28:13.676
In fact, maybe in the course
of writing the play, you may realize,

00:28:13.726 --> 00:28:15.342
“Damn, this is not it.”

00:28:17.243 --> 00:28:18.117
Something like that.

00:28:20.122 --> 00:28:22.618
Even I want something different for him.

00:28:22.682 --> 00:28:24.036
That’s also possible, right?

00:28:24.225 --> 00:28:25.514
It’s not working.

00:28:25.562 --> 00:28:27.566
What he wants is actually very simple.

00:28:27.648 --> 00:28:29.831
It’s so easy to get.

00:28:29.939 --> 00:28:32.494
So whatever obstacle you put,
he’ll get it, right?

00:28:32.580 --> 00:28:34.870
That’s what’s slightly hard.

00:28:36.912 --> 00:28:39.624
Clarifying what one really wants.
